Parents and community members of D6.

In our present world 🌎 many of us rely heavily on the internet to stay connected, do our jobs, school work and view entertainment. That’s why
Central Point School District 6 has partnered with Family Zone and ySafe to provide ongoing cyber safety education to our parent community. This partnership is to encourage a long-term commitment to the safety and digital wellbeing of our district’s patrons. This platform is a resource that parents, students, and staff can utilize for all topics around cyber safety education.
#D6Strong #D6proud #D6BetterTogether

post_text:
Crater High School 💫
Bond Update
Ground breaking for the student and event parking lot. Due to social distancing and safety, we decided to make a video of the ground breaking and have a bit of fun.

The student and event parking lot. is finally being paved, thanks to our amazing community for passing the bond. We can hardly wait to be able to hold events again, to welcome our community to join us &
have a beautifully paved lot for you to park in. The students are going really enjoy not having to navigate the large potholes and dust when they come to school. #D6Strong #D6proud #D6BetterTogether
#StayHealthy #StaySafe

* Notes
· This is a Bond Funded Project – voters passed bond in May of 2019
· Expected completion date is in late October
· Students did not drive truck. They only sat in it and it was not running.
· The owner, Mike Taylor, who is a professional racer drove the truck.
· The parking lot was closed during the event with CPPD on site.
· Students were not at the site during the event, but joined us afterwards for the video footage.
· Total time of the truck use was less than 2 minutes and the dust dissipated quickly
· This was a planned stunt - CPPD leadership and D6 Administration were involved and approved of this planned event.

UPDATE July 25th, 2020

D6 Return to Learn—plans for the 2020-21 school year
District 6 schools will be open on September 8th, to the maximum extent possible, AND families will have control and choice about the best “school” option for their child. Families may choose a 100% digital option for at home learning, a hybrid option, or a full-time on-site option. Every option includes your child’s regular classroom teacher(s) and allows students to easily move between remote and “on site” programs. Please click this link for more detailed information about plans for the school year. Este es un enlace a los planes para el año escolar 2020-21 en español .

post_text:
Back to school plans for D6 schools will be released on July 24th
D6 Families, the Oregon Department of Education will release updated guidance for schools on July 21st--expect to see our plan for re-opening D6 schools by July 24th. Our plans are designed with options to meet every families’ needs and you’ll have a clear picture of the choices for your student. Additional details for the plans are part of the required “Operational Blueprints” which will be submitted to the Jackson County Health Department on August 15th and released to our families once approved. If you have questions or concerns, please feel free to contact me: samantha.steele@district6.org or 541-840-5644 (mobile).

Samantha Steele
Superintendent
Central Point School District 6

#D6Strong #D6proud #D6BetterTogether

I want to thank everyone involved in the D6 Express delivering lunches, picking up and delivering homework all over School District 6 boundaries with 12 busses involved. post_text:
Attached is our summer meals flyer!

Please please please share this with your staff and families, we want to make sure everyone knows that we will be continuing to serve grab and go meals for most of the summer. Our 4 school sites will continue to operate like they have been, we will be running a modified mobile meal route, and offering a weekly meal pick up option. Our website is up to date and has all of this information as well!

Sharing this with all of your families is very important as participation is key for this to be financially feasible for our program. We are like our own small business with in our district and we are doing our best to maintain our revenue flow and a balanced budget. The majority of our funding comes from the Federal government and that funding is based solely on the meals we serve. As of right now we haven't received any government aid or any additional funding to help our program. Which is why I ask that you spread this far and wide and help us continue serving as many families as possible.

I did schedule an end to grab and go meals on August 14th. After that we will continue our weekly meal pick up option to close out summer!

http://www.schoolnutritionandfitness.com/index.php?sid=0506121807003006

Congratulations from the staff of D6.
The staff at D6 has some notes & messages to share with you. Visit the link below to view the messages. 🎓🧡🖤🤍

Traditionally we would have spent this day seeing you as you parade down the halls of your past schools in your caps and gowns. We would have been given the chance to congratulate you personally. Some of us have not seen you daily since you where in our classes years ago, some of us had you in classes up to March, but were not given the chance to say a proper goodbye. We are all invested in you and your success, we all share in the pride of your accomplishments. We are D6 and you are AMAZING. ❤️

UPDATE ON PRODUCE PICK UP...

FREE CSA - Produce Boxes - Wednesday, May 27

The boxes are first come first serve and we have limited supply.

Distribution for 5/27/20

Pick up can be done at any of our locations below. Nothing is required for pick up, if you are there and we have boxes left, we will give you one!

CPE, Jewett, Patrick and Crater HS will be distributing during their meal times. Our goal is that our volunteers will be distributing from 11:15am - 1pm.

**Note - This is a volunteer program, locations & times are in accordance to the volunteers available to distribute the boxes. D6 is only acting as a distribution site and does not control the locations, times or quanity of the boxes availiable. This is a first come first serve.

Please remember to visit the web page for weekly updates on distribution locations and times.

http://www.schoolnutritionandfitness.com/index.php?sid=0506121807003006

post_text:
Join us at 7pm for a Family Game Night of Trivia for Kids.

Trivia questions are aimed towards kids.

Example of how to answer in the comments sections.
Let say the correct answer is number 1 "Arm".

Here are acceptable options of comment:
"1 Arm"
"ARM"
"arm"
"1"
"arm i guess"
"i'm sure it is aRm"

Not acceptable options of comment:
"ArmIThink"
"1arm"
"Armmmmm"
"111111"

As you see we ignore letter case and can use just a number or a just text to identify the answer.

post_text:
Attention ...... D6 Families with K-11th grade children.
Last year I was able to visit schools and ask random students “What advice they had for the graduating seniors of 2020?”
I simply explained what “advice” was and then filmed their answers. What resulted, was the best 6 minute video of the year. *See video from last year attached.

This year I can not visit your children at their schools and I am so sad not to be able to be there to film them, but I am hoping with your help we can still make this video for our graduating seniors.

If you are willing, you only need a smart phone and a quiet area to simply ask your K-11th grade child “What advice they would give to the seniors who are graduating and leaving school to start their new adult lives?” “What do they think those seniors need to know?” (Best if their answers are under 20secs.)
Then hold your smart phone horizontally and film their responses and upload that video to this link in my dropbox.
https://www.dropbox.com/request/2NCQFHbcF1bfNCfrcaIf

If we can get at least 15+ videos collected, I can make a new video for the class of 2020 that will air at their graduation on June 3rd.

Know I miss your students everyday & thank you in advance for sharing their wisdom with us.
-Mrs. LeCornu

We wanted to do something special for the seniors of 2020. The fact that our seniors are not able to be together on the day of their graduation is a hard fact to take, but safety first & their well being is the priority. To help mark their upcoming graduation 🎓 we have designed a mosaic poster celebrating the seniors of Crater. The mosaic is made up of all the seniors of 2020 & each senior will receive a poster to keep.
(Make sure to zoom in to see all their faces.)
We are so proud of you all. 👏🏼👏🏼#CraterClassOf2020Strong

post_text:
May’s D6 Virtual Art Show
Second showing.
The first show was amazing and we are excited to see what you have been making since then.

You are invited to submit a photo of a piece of art you (or your child) have made. No age restrictions, any piece of art you made from any media, from drawing, painting, coloring, sculpture, wood, logos, photo ect. All are invited to submit art projects, adults as well.
(*Note- please only submit art that was not included in April’s showing. )

The only rule is art piece must be school appropriate & family friendly.
We appreciate all art, but please respect that children are welcome on this page. 😊

Art photos can be posted in the comments below or emailed to me at d6social@distrct6.org. Submissions are accepted through May 20th, 2020 to be included in the montage video, tentatively scheduled to premiere Memorial Day May 25th.
Please, try to submit photo of art with a solid color background or if a flat medium, crop photo to include only the art.
#D6BetterTogether #D6ArtShow
#ShareTheArt

🖤🧡🎓It’s time to start celebrating the Crater High school graduating class of 2020. 🎓🧡🖤

We might not all be together, but we can celebrate together & honor the class of 2020’s accomplishment.

Tomorrow we will be displaying all senior yard signs, in front of the Crater Performing Arts Center on third Street.

We invite the community to drive by and take a look. Seniors are welcome to come down to the high school and pick up their personalized yard signs beginning Friday from 10 AM to 2 PM. If you cannot come down on Friday you can stop by your school‘s main office starting Monday at 9 AM and pick up your custom yard sign.

🥳 Congratulations to the Class of 2020.🎓🧡🖤🤍🎉 We are incredibly proud of you all.

Keep checking back for more information on our celebrations of the Crater Class of 2020!
#D6PROUD #CRATERNATION #D6STRONG

shared_text:
Sams Valley Elementary School
May 6 at 1:56 PM ·

Special things are happening between students and teachers still during this COVID-19 closure! This is an example of the commitment our teachers have for D6 kids. Mrs. Rees noticed during a zoom meeting that one of her students really needed a "pick me up." She contacted the parent and asked if she could come do a social distant teddy bear picnic outside their home gate. The kinder student brought her brother, wore her princess dress, they met in the driveway, soaked up the sun, read a story, had a little treat, and filled her empty tank back up!

Again, this is just one example. We have been scheduling individual zoom meetings to offer help, we have been helping families in need, we have teachers going the extra mile to connect with kids. Our goal is to meet kids where they are and provide that individual attention to meet their needs. I am so proud to say we take care of our little hawks! #hawkssoar #D6BetterTogether #d6strong #svecpsd6
text:
#D6BetterTogether ! ❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️

Sams Valley Elementary School
May 6 at 1:56 PM ·

Special things are happening between students and teachers still during this COVID-19 closure! This is an example of the commitment our teachers have for D6 kids. Mrs. Rees noticed during a zoom meeting that one of her students really needed a "pick me up." She contacted the parent and asked if she could come do a social distant teddy bear picnic outside their home gate. The kinder student brought her brother, wore her princess dress, they met in the driveway, soaked up the sun, read a story, had a little treat, and filled her empty tank back up!

Again, this is just one example. We have been scheduling individual zoom meetings to offer help, we have been helping families in need, we have teachers going the extra mile to connect with kids. Our goal is to meet kids where they are and provide that individual attention to meet their needs. I am so proud to say we take care of our little hawks! #hawkssoar #D6BetterTogether #d6strong #svecpsd6

post_text:
|Happy May Days | Plant Sale U P D A T E | May Flowers!

The Crater FFA Plant Sale 🌱 website will be active and available starting MAY 1, 2020.
.
We are so EXCITED for our upcoming (first ever) Online Plant Sale! The Link will drop on the Central Point District 6 Webpage (https://www.district6.org/) on MAY 1.

To get ready, below is a list of our plant inventory and prices. All plants, photos, prices, and sizes will be on the Crater FFA Plant Sale Website.

Due to COVID19 regulations, no customers will be allowed in the greenhouses. Curbside Pickup ONLY.

Curbside Pickup Location: Crater High School
Enter - From HWY99
Exit - N 3rd Street

To allow for traffic flow, vehicles will be entering into the high school through HWY99, and exit onto 3rd street. This will allow us to manage vehicle traffic through the high school

Curbside Pickup Dates:
May 1: 2pm-6pm
May 2: 10am-5pm
May 5: 2pm-6pm
May 8: 2pm-6pm
May 9: 10am-5pm

Thank you for your continued support of Crater FFA and the Crater High School Horticulture Program!
.
Moving our plant sale virtual is a new experience for all of us, with only a limited number of volunteers, you may expect some curbside wait times.
.
We cannot wait to see you soon!
.
New this year (other than hanging flower pouches) is our specialty Freedom Combo: $28
(Superbena Whiteout, Blue Angelonia, and Really Red Supertunia)

ALSO, we have portulaca 4packs in Happy Hour Multicolor mix and Happy Trails White! It got missed on our original post.
.

#Craterffa #CraterBIS #Craterhorticulture #Cratergreenhouses #plants #craterplants #plantsale #craterplantsale20 #BaileyCorcoranisasuperstar

Two amazing seniors from Crater BIS have taken on a project, with a goal to highlight every Crater 2020 senior, from BIS-CAHPS-REN. They have made all the graphics and I know have put hours into making each senior highlight special.
Please "like" and follow & share their page. Crater High School Class of 2020

This page is for ALL Crater senior 2020 graduates! Instead of complaining about our senior year we are here to CELEBRATE ! If you are a senior or a parent and would like to be featured please use the contact information and provide the students name, a picture, plans for after high school, (college, military, trade, work, etc.) major and/or minor! Thank you and Go Comets !
We are also on instagram @craterhighclassof2020

These seniors are our future and we are so proud of each and every one. To the ladies that have taken on this project.... Well done and we applaud you. So proud. #D6Proud #D6Strong #D6BetterTogether #SGN
Some Good News

post_text:
ONLY THREE MORE DAYS. 🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻
PLEASE REMEMBER I need your help....

Teacher Appreciation week is May 4th - 8th, 2020

With classrooms closed, not being able to see their students in person daily, quarantine & our world tilted. We appreciate our teachers & staff more than ever. We want them to know that we appreciate all their efforts to stay connected with their students, that we see how hard they have worked to develop a new way of teaching. That we appreciate how they have gone above and beyond to make D6 Connected work.

Can you help us collect media “thanking the teachers, telling them how awesome they are, ect?”
1. Make a short video
2. Send them a handwritten thank you note, even an email works?
3. Share a Thank you photo?

We’d love to see the students & even the community tell these amazing teachers they are appreciated.

If you choose to accept this mission.... 😃
Below is the media needed to complete this project, if you choose to submit media for the montage video.

Of course you can send media or notes directly to your teacher if you wish.

Deadline for media & video clips submitted is April 30th 9pm.

Final video will be edited and premiered May 6th, 2020.

Tips to submit a photo with a sign or a photo of a note….
Make sure sign is written with a big enough font to easily read.

Tips to film a video clip.

Film horizontally & clips can be 17 seconds maximum.

Any smart phone with video capabilities is acceptable.

If possible, go to camera settings and change settings to 1080i although 720i works as well.

Tips & tricks to filming.
1. Try to find natural light facing subject. Best if the sun is not directly shinning through the window, on face or outside. Even lighting is best. Look out for shadows and avoid overhead lighting and back lighting.
2. Set up so that subject is slightly off center in the camera frame, left or right.
3. Aim camera lens just slightly above subjects eye line.
4. Place subject in the camera frame to fill one third of the frame. leaving approx 6” showing above subjects head.
5. Remember to check your background space. Keep your background as clean and simple as possible or use nature outside.
6. Audio.... try to find a quiet space with out a lot of ambient noise. Encourage strong voice when speaking.

Once photos & video clips are ready, email me at D6Social@district6.org with a subject line of “D6 Teacher” or upload media to this link.
https://www.dropbox.com/request/TWSpcHaYDMYmqNLQZb7i

Feel free to email me with any questions as well. 😊
Thank you in advance for helping make this extra special this year.
-Kimbra LeCornu
#D6BetterTogether

post_text:
We need your help....

Teacher Appreciation week May 4th - 8th, 2020

With classrooms closed, not being able to see their students in person daily, quarantine & our world tilted. We appreciate our teachers & staff more than ever. We want them to know that we appreciate all their efforts to stay connected with their students, that we see how hard they have worked to develop a new way of teaching. That we appreciate how they have gone above and beyond to make D6 Connected work.

Can you help us collect media “thanking the teachers, telling them how awesome they are?”
1. Make a short video
2. Send them a handwritten thank you note, even an email works?
3. Share a Thank you photo?

We’d love to see the students & even the community tell these amazing teachers they are appreciated.

If you choose to accept this mission.... 😃
Below is the media needed to complete this project, if you choose to submit media for the montage video.

Of course you can send media or notes directly to your teacher if you wish.

Deadline for media & video clips submitted is April 25th 9pm.

Final video will be edited and premiered 6th, 2020.

Tips to submit a photo with a sign or a photo of a note….
Make sure sign is written with a big enough font to easily read.

Tips to film a video clip.

Film horizontally & clips can be 17 seconds maximum.

Any smart phone with video capabilities is acceptable.

If possible, go to camera settings and change settings to 1080i although 720i works as well.

Tips & tricks to filming.
1. Try to find natural light facing subject. Best if the sun is not directly shinning through the window, on face or outside. Even lighting is best. Look out for shadows and avoid overhead lighting and back lighting.
2. Set up so that subject is slightly off center in the camera frame, left or right.
3. Aim camera lens just slightly above subjects eye line.
4. Place subject in the camera frame to fill one third of the frame. leaving approx 6” showing above subjects head.
5. Remember to check your background space. Keep your background as clean and simple as possible or use nature outside.
6. Audio.... try to find a quiet space with out a lot of ambient noise. Encourage strong voice when speaking.

Once photos & video clips are ready, email me at D6Social@district6.org with a subject line of “D6 Teacher” for a link to upload & share media.

Feel free to email me with any questions as well. 😊
Thank you in advance for helping make this extra special this year. -Kimbra LeCornu
#D6BetterTogether

shared_text:
Central Point School District 6
April 8 at 5:12 PM ·

D6 Virtual Art Show

You are invited to submit a photo of a “Positive themed” piece of art you (or your child) have made. No age restrictions, any piece of art you made from any media, from drawing, painting, coloring, sculpture, wood, logos, photo ect. All are invited to submit art projects, adults as well.

The only rule is art piece must be school appropriate & family friendly.
We appreciate all art, but please respect that children are welcome on this page. 😊
Art photos can be posted in the comments below or emailed to d6social@distrct6.org. Submissions are accepted through April 15th, 2020 to be included in montage video.
Please, try to submit photo of art with a solid color background or if a flat medium, crop photo to include only the art.
#D6BetterTogether

D6 Frontline staff are AMAZING.

D6 is proud to recognize all of the hard-working support staff employees who go above and beyond for our students and our District. Jackson County Health and Fire District 3 is looking for students who are interested in making a short 10-15 second video to show how they are staying connected while staying at home. I am wondering if either of you can help me identify students that would like to participate in this or put me in contact with someone who could help me coordinate this?

In the video, the student can answer one or both of the following questions:
1. Staying home doesn’t just protect you, it protects your loved ones. Who are you staying home for?
2. What are you doing to stay connected at home? (Examples could be virtual watch parties, virtual book clubs, online games, and more!)

Videos can be emailed directly to kayla@jcorcovid19.org

post_text:
We talk a lot about what this transition has been like for our students & families, but this transition has been hard on our teachers & staff as well. We don’t just miss our students we worry about them, love them & work so hard every day 24/7 to stay connected to them. #WeareD6 #D6BetterTogether
・・・
Week 2 of #distancelearning in Oregon. Not gonna lie, I was feeling pretty beat up yesterday after getting the {inevitable} news that public schools would be closed in Oregon through the end of the school year; my first year of teaching 💔
But, you know what hasn’t changed?? How the kids always make it better 👏🎉👌 We had our daily class @zoom_video_communications meeting today and I came out feeling re-energized and even more PROUD to be their teacher 😭👩‍🏫🥰 We have been focusing on #perserverance this week. And yesterday’s writing assignment was to explain what positive self-talk has to do with perseverance. I gave some examples and have loved using the @characterstrong & PAX Behavior curriculum to help continue navigating emotions with my students through this historical time. Their challenge was to write their favorite positive affirmation on their mirror where they could see it and say it each day. Shout out to my girl @msrachelhollis 💛
All this being said, my students never cease to amaze me with their creativity and their spirit! They *crack* me up 🤪
🌟✨💛
So, in order to continue to keep the positive energy alive, I wanted to send some #easterseason home! The kiddo that gets the #goldenegg is next week’s online Class Leader!! 💛
Thanks for reading this far & sharing in the #smalljoys educators have during this #Eggstremely crazy time! 🤪

Sending you all love & light! Remember to stay on the *sunny side up* ☀️🍳🥚and stay safe & healthy my friends! 😘
💛
#quarantinedteacher #eggcellent #eggpuns #4thgradeteacher #quarantinecrazy #iteach4th #easterseason #quarantineaster #goldenegg #oregon #oregonpublicschools #positivity #gratitudeattitude

#BeTheLightOR:
Tonight, we will be turning on the stadium lights at Crater as a symbol of hope and support for all of our K-12 students.

As we all go through these unprecedented times. may the lights remind you of hope.

We will turn the lights on at 20:20 military time (8:20 pm), in honor of our seniors as we join the nations school districts as they also light the way.

The lights will remain on for 20 minutes. Please feel free to drive-by and show your support.

We ask that you continue to be mindful of social distancing guidelines.

#WeareD6 #D6BetterTogether
#WeSupportOurSeniors
#WeMissOurStudents
#BeTheLightOR
#D6SeniorsAreLoved

D6 Virtual Art Show

You are invited to submit a photo of a “Positive themed” piece of art you (or your child) have made. No age restrictions, any piece of art you made from any media, from drawing, painting, coloring, sculpture, wood, logos, photo ect. All are invited to submit art projects, adults as well.

The only rule is art piece must be school appropriate & family friendly.
We appreciate all art, but please respect that children are welcome on this page. 😊
Art photos can be posted in the comments below or emailed to d6social@distrct6.org. Submissions are accepted through April 15th, 2020 to be included in montage video.
Please, try to submit photo of art with a solid color background or if a flat medium, crop photo to include only the art.

The Doodle Place
April 6 at 8:41 PM ·

Hello Doodlers! Just wanted to let you know there will be another FREE lesson on Facebook Live right here on the page tomorrow (Tuesday, April 7) at 3 PM!. We will be doing watercolor Easter eggs! You will need watercolor paper or a heavy multimedia drawing paper, watercolor paints, a small water dish, paper towels, a pencil, some salt, and some Crayons or oil pastels. A black sharpie or permanent marker or pen is optional but great to have as well. If you don’t have paint, you can do this with crayons or markers and just draw & color in the eggs. If you have markers, I will show a trick to make them look like watercolor paints! We will be learning three new techniques… Texture with salt, wax resist, and ink patterns over watercolor. I present this lesson courtesy of Deep Space Sparkle, you can find this and many other free lessons listed at their website. More info can be found in the handouts I will include tomorrow. Let me know if you have questions, I hope to see you there!

post_text:
Calling on Crater Alumni.

The country is working together in countless ways to support one another during COVID-19. But while the majority of us stay at home, others must continue to work in public spaces providing essential and critical services in healthcare, public safety, construction, information technology, transportation, food supply service and human services. Several of those essential workers are D6 Crater High graduates.

We want to celebrate alumni who are helping us through the pandemic. Graduates, please share a photo and/or comment on this post and tell us about the essential work you are doing now so we can celebrate you and show our gratitude! We invite our community to join us in thanking you and invite you to share this post with your fellow grads in hopes that our messages of thanks will let them know how deeply we appreciate them. #WeareD6 #D6proud #D6BetterTogether

Graduates, please share a photo and/or comment on this post and tell us about the essential work you are doing now so we can celebrate you and show our gratitude! We invite our community to join us in thanking you and invite you to share this post with your fellow grads in hopes that our messages of thanks will let them know how deeply we appreciate them. #WeareD6 #D6proud #D6BetterTogether

Visit the link for more information.
http://inside.sou.edu/youth/summer

SOU Youth Programs understands that planning fun summer activities for your students may seem hard to imagine right now, but we also recognize that by summer young people will need a return to socialization, enrichment, and interactive learning! With summer still three months away, we are continuing our plans for engaging and exciting youth programs and hope you are doing the same.
It’s true that things might change, and we will respond in a way that is best for our students and staff. For now, we hope you will join us as we plan a fun, informative, and collaborative summer full of learning opportunities.

Our policies regarding cancellations for summer programming are still in place, and if you need to cancel your student’s registration for a summer day camp due to issues related to COVID-19 we will honor a full refund. As always, you can make changes to your summer day camp reservation up to one week prior to your class start date with no transfer penalties.

post_text: ❤️❤️❤️❤️ #D6BetterTogether
shared_text:
Jacqueline Galli‎Central Point School District 6
April 4 at 5:31 PM ·

I just felt it necessary to let our teachers know this:

Hey teachers, I just wanted to let you know that however this week goes down - it's all good. We're on your team. This wasn't what you signed up for, and I sort of can't believe you're actually going to attempt do this. Your life is about to become one giant conference call with two dozen nine-year-olds who have no set bedtime, and are hopped up on Captain Crunch and whatever their parents have been stress-baking for the past 12 days. What could possibly go wrong?

In light of this, our family is giving you blanket permission to do this however the heck you want for the next two months.

Your kid wants to sit on your lap while you teach long division? That's great.
Need to stress eat half a bag of Cheetos while you're trying to explain how to calculate Experimental Error? Go for it.
Feel like having morning meeting in your pajamas - all month long? It's a judgement free zone here. Lord knows that's what I'll be wearing until at least noon.
Having a panic attack because you need to check in on your parents and wanna point that Zoom camera at three straight episodes of Sponge Bob for an English assignment? Excellent plan.
Want to just sit there and ask them how their days were for 40 minutes without mentioning a single thing about MLA formatting? Please God do that.

See, I don't care if you teach my kids one more thing this semester, and this is why: Just by showing up, by checking in, by caring enough to do this freaking IMPOSSIBLE job - you've already taught them the only things I really wanted them to get out of school.

You've taught them that people are flexible - they adapt to new things.
You've taught them that people will show up for them even when it's hard.
You've taught them that communities work together for the greater good.
You've taught them the world is a good place. That even when circumstance are scary, people are good.
You've loved them enough to be there - and that's all any of us can do, is love each other through this.

Our kids will be ok. Take care of yourselves too. We love you. You've got this - and if you don't, I'm not telling.

Thank you again for all you do for the community!

shared_text:
Molly Bermea
April 1 at 5:32 PM ·

And here we go. Online school.... my thoughts... so far:

Thank Goodness to our amazing D6 Central Point School District 6 Team(s) for getting control and good communication and going way above and beyond for our kids. I have been paying attention to how other kids are doing their online school in other states and I can noticeably say we are extremely blessed with an attentive and action-oriented school district. Beyond school itself, they have created resources for our kids that not many other schools are able to or are not doing.

So as overwhelmed as you might feel, feel blessed to be in this wonderful district! :D

Scenic Middle School has put together virtual teaching blocks. No parent needed -- teachers are handling EVERYTHING via video classrooms. This is a relief. And they have help at the end of each day during open pod meetings.

Grade School is a little more "wild west" so far. haha! Which I totally get. Is anyone struggling with how to block schedule your grade-schoolers tasks for school?

I keep hearing of people stressing out about juggling work and school and kids being home. I'll share by Friday how I have laid out Serafina's school and home-life. #D6Connected1stDay

Crater Renaissance Academy added 5 new photos to the album: Today in Renaissance: April 1, 2020 — at Crater Renaissance Academy.
April 1 at 10:57 PM · Central Point, OR ·

Ms. Barber packaged and distributed 120 plus Chromebooks to Renaissance families to support online learning while Ms. Hillman saw the first batch of hard copy schoolwork off on the new D6 Express. Also today, Librarian Dawn Honnaka packaged up library books to send home while Ms. Mcadam launched her new google classroom for math students.

If your student isn't sure where to start with his or her online learning, please go to the RA website at: https://cra.district6.org/weekly-syllabi/ in order to see daily lesson plans by teacher.

We can all use some help, some days as we struggle to find our way through these unpredictable times.
The goal of this group page is to share ideas, resources and positive support for our community while practicing social distancing. #D6BetterTogher. Stay Safe, Stay Healthy & Be Kind

Maybe you know....
A great way to entrain the children for a bit.
A recipe that would bring a smile to other families.
A skill you can teach us.
A fun exercise activity you want to share.
You have a great idea to share community support while remaining safe at home.
A fun game the whole family can enjoy.
Join our Group "D6 Better Together"
We can't wait to meet you.

post_text: FD3 has some ways to stay connected. 🙌🏼😊❤️ #D6BetterTogether
shared_text:
Fire District 3
March 27 at 4:00 PM ·

It's hard to be inside more, unable to participate in normal activities, see friends or go to school. To help during this time Fire District 3 has created a schedule of online events that you can expect to see hit your news feed each week! #StayHomeSaveLives #CantStopWontStop #FD3

Monday: Monday Meals - Had a busy day and not sure what to cook? Tune in to see what our crews are making and get inspired!

Wednesday: Workout Wednesday - How to stay fit at home while practicing social distancing.

Friday: Friday Fun - Running out of ideas on what to do while at home? Check out our Friday Fun video to learn a new craft/fun activity that the whole family can enjoy!

Saturday: Storytime Saturday - Engage your child with a story read by a firefighter! A new favorite book or two will be shared each week.

Kickoff is this Saturday 3/28!

post_text:
D6 is challenging all school districts and communities to add their teddy bears to their windows and join the “Bear Hunt”. #Weareallinthistogether #D6BetterTogether
#FillOurValleyWithBears🧸❤️
Here is how it all works. 👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼

Let’s all go on a teddy bear hunt.
🧸🐻🧸🐻🧸🐻🧸
Help share the word (share this post) and show off your bears. We could all help out & bring a little joy to these challenging times. If you have a stuffed animal 🧸 who lives in your home, place them in a window for children & families to spot when out on walks (keeping a safe distance of course) or out on drives through neighborhoods.
Be kind and respectful of our bears and stay on the sidewalks.

Snap a photo & share what you find on your bear hunts in our comments below. For those who live rurally, you can play too. Send us photos of your bears living in the county. 😊🧸

Share your wild stuffed animals on display in the comments below. Stay healthy & safe as you go on a bear 🐻 hunt. #D6BetterTogether

PS. Any stuffed animals will work for our hunt. 😃

Medford School District 549C Eagle Point School District 9
Ashland Public Schools Grants Pass School District 7 Rogue River School District

post_text: Our Comets are champions to us!
shared_text:
Demi DeSoto‎Central Point School District 6
March 14 at 6:48 PM ·

Oregon State University shut down the OSAA 5A tournament in the Gill Coliseum after the boys consolation game that morning.

We packed up our NFHSnetwork.com gear and went back to the hotel. There we saw the Crater Boys and Girls team in the lobby after their team meetings, it was heartbreaking to see their suffering.

Student athletes at the peak of their careers and performances denied the opportunity to further their goals with their teammates. Coaches, parents, and fans disappointed that the potential of these teams stopped, not by their own demise, but of extenuating circumstances.

Yes, that are greater concerns of health and wellness of the human population of Earth, but that doesn't diminish the significance of the impact of the events at this grass roots level to those we know and love.

Congratulations to both Crater Boys and Girls teams, you are Champions in our eyes
text:
Our Comets are champions to us!

Oregon State University shut down the OSAA 5A tournament in the Gill Coliseum after the boys consolation game that morning.

We packed up our NFHSnetwork.com gear and went back to the hotel. There we saw the Crater Boys and Girls team in the lobby after their team meetings, it was heartbreaking to see their suffering.

Student athletes at the peak of their careers and performances denied the opportunity to further their goals with their teammates. Coaches, parents, and fans disappointed that the potential of these teams stopped, not by their own demise, but of extenuating circumstances.

Yes, that are greater concerns of health and wellness of the human population of Earth, but that doesn't diminish the significance of the impact of the events at this grass roots level to those we know and love.

Congratulations to both Crater Boys and Girls teams, you are Champions in our eyes

post_text:
Todas las escuelas del Distrito 6 cerrarán del 16 de marzo al 31 de marzo de 2020

Debido a la pandemia de COVID-19, la gobernadora Kate Brown anunció el cierre de escuelas estatal para estudiantes en Oregon del lunes 16 de marzo al martes 31 de marzo.
En un esfuerzo para prepararse para el cierre, las escuelas del Distrito 6 estarán abiertas el viernes 13 de marzo y operarán en horarios regulares. A los estudiantes se les permitirá recoger pertenencias, libros y suministros y luego regresar a casa, o los estudiantes pueden permanecer en la escuela y las clases hasta el despido regular. Los autobuses y el servicio de comida operarán en horarios regulares el viernes 13 de marzo.
Todos los eventos, reuniones y actividades del Distrito 6 y escolares previamente programados, incluidas las prácticas y competencias deportivas y actividades de OSAA, se cancelan hasta nuevo aviso.

post_text:
Crater’s Deaf Academic Brain Bowl team recently competed in the Western Regional Competition in Hawaii, where they scored high enough to earn a “Wild Card” spot and a chance to compete at the national competition, once all regional contests wrap up. “After winning our first two matches against one of the top teams in the nation, our team became the buzz of the competition… two of our players received special recognition. Samantha Castaneda received the esteemed 4-year participation award, and Aubrey Merrill received their all-star player award. The all-star player award is given to the top scoring players throughout the entire tournament,” said coach and DHH teacher, Erin Joliffe.

Crater’s Deaf Academic Brain Bowl team (AKA, The Sneaker Wave team) knows how to REPRESENT!! #Craternation #D6proud

post_text: 👏🏼👏🏼👏🏼🧡🖤🤍 Crater Speech & Debate competed in the South Oregon Student Congress and Big Questions Debate National Qualifier yesterday! This tested Crater's ability in congressional debate and Big Questions against the entire South Oregon district, and our students did exceptionally well! Out of two house chambers and one senate chamber (two students qualify from each chamber), Crater took first in both houses! This means BIS students Madelynn Hanvey and Adam Moeglein will travel to New Mexico this June to compete against students from all over the US. We have one more national qualifier in two weeks, and our fingers are crossed that we will send even more Crater students to Albuquerque. #Craternation #D6proud

........

BIS is hosting our Annual Exhibition of Learning on the evening of March 3rd 5:00 p.m.-8:00 p.m.

This event will give you a very clear picture of the learning BIS students are engaged in throughout the school year. You will see many exhibits related to science and technology, including an electric switch car, game boxes programmed by students, electric guitars built and played by students, a cultural fashion show, and this year students from the architecture and engineering class have built a clothes closet for Crater Campus.

Don’t feel like cooking? Bring your family and purchase dinner from Victory Dog’s Food Truck and a Kona Ice for dessert!

shared_text:
Jared Banry‎Central Point School District 6
February 23 at 10:33 PM ·

I’m the head coach of a middle school wrestling team in Southern Oregon. For the past 2 seasons, I have had the honor to work with a Pioneer in the sport of Women’s Wrestling. Not only did she help pave the way for the sport on the mat, she now is breaking down the walls as a coach.

As a wrestler at Red Bluff HS, in Red Bluff, California, KT Grissom was the only girl on an all boys team. As she battled the stereotypes of women wrestlers, she earned herself a spot on the inaugural Southern Oregon University Women’s Wrestling Team.

As life directed her to chase her dream of becoming a police officer, I was lucky enough to have her join my coaching staff.

KT Grissom who is currently a 911 dispatcher, has truly earned the title of coach. She has impressed me with her leadership and fearlessness as she works to break some old school hurdles.

I want to thank Coach KT Grissom for breaking the stereotypes and being an example, a roll model and mentor to both the guys and the gals on the team. You are an asset to the sport.

Crater and North Medford Speech & Debate hosted the first annual Aristoteles Invitational Speech & Debate Competition at Crater on Feb. 21-22. Nine area high schools were in attendance as students competed in events like Student Congress, Public Forum Debate, Humorous Interpretation, Extemporaneous Speaking, and more. Crater students ran the tournament and served as outstanding hosts, and many parents and community members volunteered their time as judges.

Crater's finalist and award winners include...
Congress Finalists-- Kiana Hall, Brenden Bjarnson, Josiah Hearne
Humorous Interpretation-- Katie Furrer, 2nd
Dramatic Interpretation-- Kiana Hall, 1st
Original Oratory-- Kiana Hall, 2nd
Big Questions Debate-- Kaylah Tartaglio, 2nd; Sophia Edwards and Madelynn Hanvey, 1st
Storytelling-- Gavin Bjarnson, 2nd
Lincoln Douglas Debate-- Brenden Bjarnson, 3rd
Public Forum Debate-- Madelynn Hanvey and Sophia Edwards, 3rd
Radio Commentary-- Kaylee Broadbent, Finalist

#Craternation #D6proud

post_text:
Please see the most recent update from CPPD:

PRESS RELEASE

RELEASE DATE/TIME: 2/13/20 @ 08:30am
INCIDENT DATE: 2/12/20 @ 9:00pm
INCIDENT TYPE: School Threats
CONTACT PERSON: Captain Dave Croft

On February 12th, 2020 at approximately 9pm, Officers with the Central Point Police Department took a report from a student that said his friend told him he had seen a Snapchat post from an unknown person, indicating a generalized threat to Crater High School. This social media post was not saved and has not been verified by law enforcement.

The Central Point Police Department immediately began an investigation and is actively pursuing leads to determine the source of the social media post. Central Point Police are working closely with School District 6 to assure the safety of our students and staff. The Central Point Police Department will have an increased presence on school campuses while continuing to investigate this threats report. Central Point Police Department has two School Resource Officers assigned to the schools and they are both trained in threat assessment and school safety measures. We will continue to update parents and our community on the status of this investigation.

If anyone has information regarding this case, please immediately call the Central Point Police Department at 541-664-5578, remember if you “see something, say something”

The Central Point Police Department takes every threat to our schools seriously and the safety and security of every student and staff member in our schools is our primary concern.

post_text:
Parents,
Last night, school officials and law enforcement were made aware of an anonymous and generalized threat to Crater High School, posted on social media. The Central Point Police Department and school district administrators have investigated the social media post and determined that the post does not represent an immediate or continuing threat to student or staff safety. CPPD and D6 administrators will continue to work together to further assure the safety of our students and staff, including an increased police presence on campus today. Crater is open and operating on a normal schedule today.

The safety and security of every student and staff member is our district’s primary concern and every threat, credible or not, is taken seriously and investigated. If you have specific information about a threat to school safety, please contact me, your school principal or law enforcement.

Samantha Steele,
Superintendent
541-494-6201
541-840-5644

Legally Blonde at Scenic

Scenic Middle School Drama will present its musical of the school year, “Legally Blonde the Musical Jr.,” on January 30th-February 1st at the Crater Performing Arts Center on the campus of Crater High School in Central Point, OR. Admission is $5 for students/seniors and $8 for adults. Children five and under are free. Reserved tickets can be purchased at https://app.arts-people.com/index.php?show=111390. Tickets will also be available at the door.

Based on the award-winning Broadway musical and the smash hit motion picture, “Legally Blonde the Musical JR.” is a fabulously fun journey of self-empowerment and expanding horizons. The show’s instantly recognizable songs are filled with humor, wit and sass, leaving cast members and audiences alike seeing pink!

“Legally Blonde Jr.” follows the transformation of Elle Woods as she tackles stereotypes, snobbery and scandal in pursuit of her dreams. When Elle’s college boyfriend, Warner, dumps her and heads to Harvard Law School, claiming she’s not “serious” enough, Elle takes matters into her own hands, crafting a showy song-and-dance personal essay and charming her way into law school. Befriending classmate, Emmett, and spunky hairdresser, Paulette, along the way, Elle finds that books and looks aren’t mutually exclusive. As Elle begins outsmarting her peers, she realizes that law may be her natural calling after all.

“Legally Blonde JR.” features large and energetic cast of 36 students and is a fun romp for people of all ages. The designation JR. at the end of the title indicates that though the movie was rated PG13 this version of the play is “G” rated and is appropriate for young people.

The cast features Kenna Lujan as Elle Woods, Casey Denny as Emmett Forrest, Gavin Snow as Warner Hunington III, Mia Brewer as Brooke Windham, Baylee Tiller as Paulette Bonafonté, Aleena Austin as Vivenne Kensington, and Deegan Carlson as Professor Callahan. Other cast members include Kenzie Kauzlaurich, Vanessa Brewer, Grace Davenport, Mary Norton, Madison Johnson, Ava Kerley, Penelope Spires, Shylah Fleury, Claire Davenport, Rowen Miller, Echo Smith, Daisy Ruiz, Janelle Luckaszewicz, Aesha Luckett, Zachary Mireles, Owen Caster, Ella Rose Harriman, Isabelle Montalvo Jada Harding, Savannah Herbst, Logan Kennedy, Stephanee Watkins, Josephine Montalvo, Alexia Thompson, Akira Howard, Cassidy Kerby, Hannah Veach Kaidence Kennedy, and Day James. Direction and choreography is by Scenic Middle School Drama/Dance teacher Rebecca K. Campbell.

It is our great honor to congratulate head Crater Baseball Coach, Jay Campbell, on being selected as the 2018-19 Northwest Section Baseball Coach of the Year!!!! Jay was specifically nominated by the Oregon School Activities Association as the most deserving recipient for this honor amongst coaches of the sport in Alaska, Idaho, Montana, Oregon and Wyoming. Honorees were judged upon their performance in the 2018-19 school year, lifetime community involvement, school involvement and philosophy of coaching. This selection also puts Jay into the running for National Coach of the Year!

Congratulations Jay!

Legally Blonde at Scenic

Scenic Middle School Drama will present its musical of the school year, “Legally Blonde the Musical Jr.,” on January 30th-February 1st at the Crater Performing Arts Center on the campus of Crater High School in Central Point, OR. Admission is $5 for students/seniors and $8 for adults. Children five and under are free. Reserved tickets can be purchased at https://app.arts-people.com/index.php?show=111390. Tickets will also be available at the door.

Based on the award-winning Broadway musical and the smash hit motion picture, “Legally Blonde the Musical JR.” is a fabulously fun journey of self-empowerment and expanding horizons. The show’s instantly recognizable songs are filled with humor, wit and sass, leaving cast members and audiences alike seeing pink!

“Legally Blonde Jr.” follows the transformation of Elle Woods as she tackles stereotypes, snobbery and scandal in pursuit of her dreams. When Elle’s college boyfriend, Warner, dumps her and heads to Harvard Law School, claiming she’s not “serious” enough, Elle takes matters into her own hands, crafting a showy song-and-dance personal essay and charming her way into law school. Befriending classmate, Emmett, and spunky hairdresser, Paulette, along the way, Elle finds that books and looks aren’t mutually exclusive. As Elle begins outsmarting her peers, she realizes that law may be her natural calling after all.

“Legally Blonde JR.” features large and energetic cast of 36 students and is a fun romp for people of all ages. The designation JR. at the end of the title indicates that though the movie was rated PG13 this version of the play is “G” rated and is appropriate for young people.

The cast features Kenna Lujan as Elle Woods, Casey Denny as Emmett Forrest, Gavin Snow as Warner Hunington III, Mia Brewer as Brooke Windham, Baylee Tiller as Paulette Bonafonté, Aleena Austin as Vivenne Kensington, and Deegan Carlson as Professor Callahan. Other cast members include Kenzie Kauzlaurich, Vanessa Brewer, Grace Davenport, Mary Norton, Madison Johnson, Ava Kerley, Penelope Spires, Shylah Fleury, Claire Davenport, Rowen Miller, Echo Smith, Daisy Ruiz, Janelle Luckaszewicz, Aesha Luckett, Zachary Mireles, Owen Caster, Ella Rose Harriman, Isabelle Montalvo Jada Harding, Savannah Herbst, Logan Kennedy, Stephanee Watkins, Josephine Montalvo, Alexia Thompson, Akira Howard, Cassidy Kerby, Hannah Veach Kaidence Kennedy, and Day James. Direction and choreography is by Scenic Middle School Drama/Dance teacher Rebecca K. Campbell.

Students in Mr. White's class read a Scholastic News article about the Statue of Liberty! They learned that at one point Thomas Edison had hoped to play speeches from inside the 🗽 using his newly invented phonograph.
After, they wrote a paragraph about what Lady Liberty would say if she could talk. A couple of kiddos made a torch for them to hold while presenting! Here are some pics from their presentations with videos to follow.

ARE YOU READY FOR SOME FOOTBALL
🏈 🧡🖤🧡🏈
TODAY IS THE STATE CHAMPIONSHIP GAME!!!!

Be part of the fan send off for our team, band & cheerleaders as they are escorted to the freeway, the bus departs Crater High School at 1:20 pm. (Details at the bottom.)

Kick off at 5:00pm
Location, Roseburg High School.
Adults $10, Students $5
To purchase tickets online or get broadcast information please visit osaa.org. Tickets can also be purchased at the game.

Watch for game updates & photos right here on D6 Facebook.

GO COMETS!!!!
#Craternation #D6BetterTogether #D6proud #OSAA

FAN SEND OFF DETAILS.
Crater will be doing a big send off. The bus will depart Crater HS at 1:20 pm on Stadium Way, head up N. 3rd then hit Pine Street towards Pilot where they’ll get on I-5 and head North.
Please help us get the word out, we'd love to line the streets along their path and have a train behind them! They've made history and we want to show them how proud we are. GO COMETS!!!!!

post_text:
CRATER FOOTBALL HEADING TO STATE CHAMPIONSHIP GAME!!!!

Congratulations to our Crater Comet Football team for making school history with a win over West Albany at the semifinals game Saturday night at Autzen Stadium and advancing to the State Championship game this coming weekend! This final game will be played Saturday Nov 30th at 5:00 at Roseburg High School.
Adults $10, Students $5
To purchase tickets online or get broadcast information please visit osaa.org. Tickets can also be purchased at the game.
We will be sending a rooter bus again, students need to sign up with the bookkeeper. First 50 students to return their permission slip and $5 will get a seat.
We will also be doing a fan send off for our team as they are escorted to the freeway, their bus departs Crater High School at 1:20 pm.
This will be a WHITE OUT game. GO COMETS!!!!
#Craternation #D6BetterTogether #D6proud #OSAA

Crater Football Headed to State Semifinals at Autzen Stadium!!!

Congratulations to our Crater Football team for advancing to the 5A State Semifinals!! The game will be this Saturday, Nov 23rd , at 5:00 pm vs. West Albany.
Location: Autzen Stadium, Eugene OR

TICKET PRICES
$10 adults, $5 students

The OSAA and GoFan are working together to bring digital ticketing to our State Championship events. Spectators will now be able to purchase their tickets online anytime including the day of the event and skip the lines. Purchase tickets by visiting https://gofan.co/app/school/OSAA. Tickets can also be purchased at the gate.

BRACKETS w/ BROADCAST LINK
http://www.osaa.org/activities/fbl/brackets

There will be a rooter bus (HIGH SCHOOL STUDENTS ONLY) heading to Autzen Stadium on Saturday, 11/23 for the game. The bus will load at 11:45 am and return after the game. Cost will be $5.00 for the bus and $5.00 for the game (bring extra money for food). Permission slips will be in the bookkeeper’s office. The first 50 students that return signed permission slip by parent/guardian and pay the bookkeeper, will get a spot on the bus. GO COMETS!!!
#Craternation #D6proud

🇺🇸 As you may know every three years it's a tradition at Scenic Middle School to design and carry out the capturing of a patriotic all-school photo.
This year, 8th Grader Mary Nadauld created the design that was chosen by a student and staff committee for this year’s picture.
Mary explained, “I chose the slogan “The Hope of America” 🇺🇸 because I believe that our generation has the ability to create a lot of hope for the very bright future of our country.” 🇺🇸

#D6pride #D6BetterTogether

If you’d like a copy of this years photo, contact the main office at Scenic Middle School before Nov. 21st. For orders and pricing.

shared_text:
Sams Valley Elementary School
November 6, 2019 at 5:23 AM ·

Late this afternoon, we started having some issues with our pump on our well. Maintenance worked diligently throughout the evening and determined at 8:00 PM that the pump needs to be replaced. I have been assured that the well will be fully functional by Thursday.

This will leave us needing to function for part or all of the school day tomorrow without the well, but we will have water. While it will be slightly disruptive to some of our normal routine, there will be very little change to the classroom environment. We believe that attendance at school is vital for student learning and the staff is committed to minimizing any interference with the normal schedule. Besides drinking from water bottles, washing their hands at hand sanitizing stations, and possibly using portable toilets, students will have a normal day at school.

Our storage tank is currently partially full (and filling at a very, very, slow rate overnight) and in the event it runs dry we will have 12 portable restrooms and multiple hand sanitizing stations delivered in the morning. Bottled water will be available for staff and students and the food service staff will be able to bring in water to serve both breakfast and lunch.

As always, we believe you know your child best, so please proceed as you feel comfortable. If you feel it’s best to keep your child home, we respect your decision. If you feel like your child can handle these accommodations, than we would love to see them here in the morning! For those children that still attend tomorrow, they are welcome to bring their own water bottles, but please know we will have bottled water available for them. If you have any questions, please don’t hesitate to contact the school office at 541-494-6870.

While it will be slightly disruptive to some of our normal routine, there will be very little change to the classroom environment. We believe that attendance at school is vital for student learning and the staff is committed to minimizing any interference with the normal schedule. Besides drinking from water bottles, washing their hands at hand sanitizing stations, and possibly using portable toilets, students will have a normal day at school.

Our storage tank is currently partially full (and filling at a very, very, slow rate overnight) and in the event it runs dry we will have 12 portable restrooms and multiple hand sanitizing stations delivered in the morning. Bottled water will be available for staff and students and the food service staff will be able to bring in water to serve both breakfast and lunch.

As always, we believe you know your child best, so please proceed as you feel comfortable. If you feel it’s best to keep your child home, we respect your decision. If you feel like your child can handle these accommodations, than we would love to see them here in the morning! For those children that still attend tomorrow, they are welcome to bring their own water bottles, but please know we will have bottled water available for them. If you have any questions, please don’t hesitate to contact the school office at 541-494-6870.

shared_text:
Crater Volleyball is with Megan Dunn at Crater High School.
October 16, 2019 at 7:28 PM · Central Point, OR ·

Senior Night...another heavy reminder of how fast life moves. One moment you’re a freshman in high school, experiencing the adrenaline of your first match. The next moment...you’re listening to an announcer queue your parents and teammates onto the court to proudly hand you a bouquet of flowers, honoring the years of hard work and dedication to your sport. And suddenly, you’re on the other side of it all as the coach. Reflecting on all of the teammates, parents, and coaches that have given more than you thought a sport could offer. Priceless memories. Meaningful relationships. Cherish ALL of it! 🙌🏼
•
Congrats to Kayana and Averi for another W on their Senior Night! 12-2 with two games to go...see you all at State! 🏐

shared_text:
Southern Oregon Sparrow Clubs
October 8, 2019 at 12:25 AM ·

Scenic Middle School launched their FIRST SPARROW CLUB in 15 years today!!!! 🎉 🎊 🎉 🎊🎉🎊🎉
Because of a compassionate and determined group of young leadership students reaching out to Sparrow Clubs, the Spartans will have this amazing opportunity to serve others in honor of their Sparrow, Miya.

You could hear a pin drop today during this emotional and inspiring assembly. Students were moved to compassion as they learned about the journey 6-year-old Miya has been on since birth. This sweet little girl gained a whole lot of family today.

Special thanks to the club sponsor Medical Eye Center for making this possible. Your sponsorship is providing the opportunity for young people to KNOW they matter.

A HUGE thank you to Ellie Misner-Smith for being the club advisor this year. We appreciate you and your leadership students.

Let’s go #Spartans!!!!

#sparrowunited #sparrowclubs #scoliosis #warrior

💚💚💚💚💚💚💚💚

Fire District 3
October 1, 2019 at 11:15 PM ·

This afternoon Fire District 3 celebrated the construction progress of the new Scenic Fire Station in Central Point.

Partner agencies including, Central Point School District 6, Scenic Middle School, City of Central Point (City Hall), Housing Authority of Jackson County, Adroit Construction Co., and Soderstorm Architects were present to answer questions pertaining to the station which will be operational in June of 2020.

The Scenic Middle School 7th and 8th grade Leadership classes were also there to help us celebrate the new build. Take a look at the photos below, maybe one day some of those faces will be working at Fire District 3! #furefirefighter #construction #partnership #community

post_text: Creativity is such an important skill to have in a world of ever changing technology & a future workforce for careers yet to be invented. A well rounded skill set is a must for tomorrow’s world. 👏🏼👏🏼👏🏼👏🏼 #MakerspaceForTheWin #D6pride #D6BetterTogether
shared_text:
Sams Valley Elementary School
September 20, 2019 at 1:05 PM ·

The students are now actively using the makerspace! Mrs. Gentry's class has been learning about food, gardening, cooking, and nutrition. They took a visit to wandering roots and expanded upon their learning with a kitchen utensil woodburning project. They had to make a prototype drawing of their design, and then transfer that design to a wooden utensil. The students not only learn to use a woodburner, but they develop core values such as patience and persistance, and learn that sometimes success comes with appropriate struggle. I am so proud of these 4th graders and their engagement in project based learning! #hawkssoar #cpsd6

CESPN helps make GAMEDAY happen! Students work hard to bring #CraterNation a live event to be proud of. Last Friday, we were fortunate to have Andryanna Sheppard - Journalist for KDRV NewsWatch 12 come out to The Dutch and do a short feature on rising sophomore and CESPN superstar, Ayden Merklein pregame. Then the rest of the crew came and did a fabulous job filming, producing and creating an exciting game day.
